{"type":"message","id":"fae6340b","parentId":"1ffee4b6","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:53:21.585Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_con0tm2wfh4o_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 105015\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what single concrete action would advance the goals.\r\n\r\nLooking at the pending actions:\r\n1. CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n2. Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n3. Distinguish \"constant format\" (freq=60, CFI=1) from \"research trajectory\" (freq<60, CFI>0.7)\r\n4. Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n5. Design actual compression network (currently only analyzed text invariants)\r\n\r\nThe most immediate next step based on the Phase 1 CFI Analysis results is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. The key finding was that only 5.7% of invariants have high CFI (>=0.7), and 44.8% are pure noise (CFI=0).\r\n\r\nLet me look at what files exist and what would be a concrete action. I should check the research directory structure to understand what's available.\r\n\r\nActually, looking at the goals, the next logical step is to design and implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would involve:\r\n1. Creating a new experiment that weights compression by CFI values\r\n2. Comparing prediction quality vs the frequency baseline\r\n\r\nLet me check what files exist in the research directory to understand the current state better.\r\n\r\nActually, I need to be careful here. I should look at existing files to understand the data format and what baseline exists. Let me check what files are available.\r\n\r\nBut wait - I don't have a way to directly list files. I need to infer from the context what's available. The key document mentioned is `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` which contains the analysis.\r\n\r\nA concrete next action would be to:\r\n1. Design the CFI-weighted compression experiment specification\r\n2. Or implement a simple script to test CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete action: design the CFI-weighted compression experiment specification.\r\n\r\n\r\nI'll craft a precise specification for the experimental comparison. I'll focus on creating a structured approach that allows for clear, measurable insights into compression effectiveness.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\nLooking at the current state: Phase 1 CFI Analysis is complete with key findings about noise (44.8% CFI=0) and causal anchors (5.7% CFI≥0.7). The next logical step is designing the CFI-weighted compression experiment to test whether CFI filtering improves prediction quality over frequency baseline.\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis reveals 94.3% of frequency-invariants are either noise or weak signals. A controlled experiment comparing CFI-weighted compression vs pure frequency compression is needed to validate whether filtering to the 5.7% high-CFI tokens improves next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate experiment specification for CFI-weighted compression comparison, defining methodology, metrics, and success criteria for testing whether CFI filtering outperforms frequency baseline.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression (filtering to high-CFI invariants) will outperform frequency-based compression for next-pulse prediction by reducing metaprogramming noise contamination.\r\n\r\n## Baseline\r\n- Pure frequency compression (current approach)\r\n- Compress pulse history by keeping top-N most frequent tokens\r\n\r\n## Experimental Condition\r\n- CFI-weighted compression\r\n- Filter to invariants with CFI ≥ 0.7 (true causal anchors)\r\n- Secondary sort: frequency for tiebreaking among high-CFI tokens\r\n\r\n## Metrics\r\n1. **Next-pulse token prediction accuracy** (BLEU/Exact match on next pulse)\r\n2. **Compression ratio** (tokens retained / total tokens)\r\n3. **Signal-to-noise ratio** (high-CFI tokens / total tokens)\r\n\r\n## Test Corpus\r\n- Use last 10 completed pulses as held-out test set\r\n- Train compression on pulses 1-N, predict pulse N+1\r\n- Cross-validate across multiple pulse ranges\r\n\r\n## Success Criteria\r\n- CFI-weighted method achieves ≥10% improvement in prediction accuracy\r\n- OR demonstrates that high-CFI tokens alone (5.7% of vocabulary) capture ≥80% of predictive signal\r\n\r\n## Implementation Steps\r\n1. Extract token frequency counts from pulse history\r\n2. Extract CFI scores from `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` analysis\r\n3. Implement two compression functions (frequency-only, CFI-weighted)\r\n4. Run prediction comparison across test corpus\r\n5. Report results in `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_RESULTS.md`\r\n\r\n## Dependencies\r\n- `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` (CFI analysis data)\r\n- Pulse history files (`pulse_*.md`)\r\n- Token frequency data from compression analysis\r\nfile: research/CFI_EXPERIMENT_SPEC.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:50:47\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774364001581}}
